<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-02-01T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-02-01T13:00:00-05:00" n="1" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">810.20 Defense/577<hi rend="superscript">2/4</hi>: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Colombia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Braden</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Bogotá</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-02-01T13:00:00-05:00">February 1, 1941—1
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 2:22 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>45. My telegram No. 31, January 27.<note n="2" xml:id="d1fn2">Not
                                printed.</note> In conversation with President<note n="3" xml:id="d1fn3">Eduardo Santos.</note> last night it was opportune
                            for me informally to mention possibility we would desire to make survey
                            of Old Providence Island and Cartagena. President readily assented but
                            requested that officers and equipment sent for this purpose be
                            temporarily attached to Naval Mission.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Braden</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>